[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1853-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] The **1853 Tennessee gubernatorial election** was held on August 4, 1853, to elect the Governor of Tennessee.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1853-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] Democratic nominee and former member of the U.S.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1853-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] House of Representatives from Tennessee's 1st district Andrew Johnson defeated Whig nominee Gustavus Adolphus Henry Sr.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1853-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] On election day, August 4, 1853, Democratic nominee Andrew Johnson won the election by a margin of 2,252 votes against his Whig opponent Gustavus Adolphus Henry Sr., thereby gaining Democratic control over the office of Governor.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1853-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] Johnson was sworn in as the 15th Governor of Tennessee on October 17, 1853.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1855-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] The **1855 Tennessee gubernatorial election** was held on August 2, 1855, to elect the governor of Tennessee.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1855-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Democratic governor Andrew Johnson was re-elected against Whig nominee and former member of the U.S.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1855-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] House of Representatives from Tennessee's 7th district Meredith Poindexter Gentry.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1855-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] On election day, August 2, 1855, incumbent Democratic governor Andrew Johnson won re-election by a margin of 2,157 votes against his Whig opponent Meredith Poindexter Gentry, thereby retaining Democratic control over the office of governor.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1855-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] Johnson was sworn in for his second term on October 17, 1855.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] The **1864 National Union National Convention** was the United States presidential nominating convention of the National Union Party, which met in Baltimore, Maryland on June 7 and 8, 1864.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] National Union was the name adopted by the main faction of the Republican Party in a coalition with many, if not most, War Democrats and Unconditional Unionists after some Republicans and War Democrats nominated John C.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] Frémont over Lincoln a few weeks earlier.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] The National Union renominated Abraham Lincoln for president and Andrew Johnson was nominated for vice president.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] During the convention, the party adopted a platform calling for a victorious end in the ongoing Civil War, the eradication of slavery by constitutional amendment and the enforcement of the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] The party name was created in May 1864, during the Civil War, ahead of the 1864 presidential election, in which President Abraham Lincoln, then a Republican, was running for reelection.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] Frémont, who had been the Republicans' first presidential nominee during the 1856 election.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] It was hoped that this act would cause someone other than Lincoln to gain the Republican nomination.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] Republicans loyal to Lincoln created a new name for their party at the convention in Baltimore, Maryland, during the first week in June 1864, in order to accommodate the War Democrats who supported the war and wished to separate themselves from the Copperheads.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] The convention dropped then-Vice President Hannibal Hamlin, a Radical Republican from the ticket, and chose War Democrat Andrew Johnson as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] The National Unionists hoped that the new party and the Lincoln–Johnson ticket would stress the national character of the war.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] The party supported a Platform of 11 resolutions.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] Dennis Francis Murphy, member of the Official Corps of Reporters for the U.S.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] On the first ballot, Missouri delegates cast their 22 votes for General Ulysses S.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] The Missourians quickly changed their votes to make Lincoln's renomination unanimous.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] Though Hamlin was willing to serve another term as vice president, he privately made it known that he was willing to step aside if a candidate who would be a greater electoral asset to Lincoln could be found.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] The convention therefore nominated Andrew Johnson, the military governor of Tennessee.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] Lincoln had refused to weigh in on his preferred running mate, and the convention chose to nominate Johnson, a Southern War Democrat, in order to boost the party's appeal to Unionists of both parties.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-national-union-national-convention] In keeping with the tradition of the time, Lincoln did not attend the convention.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 8, 1864, near the end of the American Civil War.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent President Abraham Lincoln of the National Union Party easily defeated the Democratic nominee, former General George B.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan, by a wide margin of 212–21 in the electoral college, with 55% of the popular vote.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] For the election, the Republican Party and some Democrats created the National Union Party, especially to attract War Democrats.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Despite some intra-party opposition from Salmon Chase and the Radical Republicans, Lincoln won his party's nomination at the 1864 National Union National Convention.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Rather than re-nominate Vice President Hannibal Hamlin, the convention selected Andrew Johnson of Tennessee, a War Democrat, as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats were divided between the Copperheads, who favored immediate peace with the Confederacy, and War Democrats, who supported the war.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 Democratic National Convention nominated McClellan, a War Democrat, but adopted a platform advocating peace with the Confederacy, which McClellan rejected, although his running mate George H.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] While the Confederacy seemed to have survival potential in summer 1864, it was visibly collapsing by election day in November.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Despite his early fears of defeat, Lincoln won strong majorities in the popular and electoral vote, partly as a result of the recent Union victory at the Battle of Atlanta.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] As the Civil War was still raging, no electoral votes were counted from any of the eleven southern states that had joined the Confederate States of America.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln's re-election ensured that he would preside over the successful conclusion of the Civil War.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln's victory made him the first president to win re-election since Andrew Jackson in 1832, as well as the first Northern president to ever win re-election.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln was assassinated six weeks into his second term.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] He was succeeded by his vice president, Andrew Johnson, who favored quick restoration of the seceded states to the Union without protection for the former slaves.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] This led to conflict with the Republican-dominated Congress, culminating in Johnson's impeachment by the House of Representatives in 1868; he was acquitted in the Senate by one vote.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 presidential election took place during the American Civil War.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] According to the Miller Center for the study of the presidency, the election was noteworthy for occurring at all, an unprecedented democratic exercise in the midst of a civil war.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Republican dissidents who called themselves Radical Republicans formed a party named the Radical Democratic Party and nominated John C.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont as their candidate for president.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont later withdrew and endorsed Lincoln.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] War Democrats joined with Republicans as the National Union Party, with Lincoln at the head of the ticket.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The National Union Party was a temporary name used to attract War Democrats and Southern Border State Unionists who would not vote for the Republican Party.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] It faced off against the regular Democratic Party, including Peace Democrats.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 presidential election conventions of the parties are considered below in order of the party's popular vote.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] As the Civil War progressed, political opinions within the Republican Party began to diverge.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Senators Charles Sumner and Henry Wilson from Massachusetts wanted the Republican Party to advocate constitutional amendments to prohibit slavery and guarantee racial equality before the law.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Initially, not all northern Republicans supported such measures.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic leaders hoped that the radical Republicans would put forth their own ticket in the election.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The *New York World* newspaper, particularly interested in undermining the National Union Party, ran a series of articles predicting a delay for the National Union Convention until late in 1864 to allow Frémont time to collect delegates to win the nomination.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont supporters in New York City established a newspaper called the *New Nation*, which declared in one of its initial issues that the National Union Convention would be a "nonentity".
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The *New York World* also published false information (further purported by Samuel S.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Before the election, some War Democrats joined the Republicans to form the National Union Party.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] With the outcome of the Civil War still in doubt, some political leaders, including Salmon P.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Chase, Benjamin Wade, and Horace Greeley, opposed Lincoln's re-nomination on the grounds that he could not win.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Chase himself became the only candidate to contest Lincoln's re-nomination actively, but he withdrew in March when a slew of Republican officials, including some within the state of Ohio upon whom Chase's campaign depended, endorsed Lincoln for re-nomination.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln was still popular with most members of the Republican Party, and the National Union Party nominated him for a second term as president at their convention in Baltimore, Maryland, on June 7–8, 1864.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] With incumbent vice president Hannibal Hamlin remaining indifferent about the prospect of a second term in office, Andrew Johnson, the former senator from and current military governor of Tennessee, was named as Lincoln's vice presidential running-mate.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] He had been governor of Tennessee from 1853 to 1857 and was elected by the legislature to the Senate in 1857.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In his congressional service, he sought passage of the Homestead Bill which was enacted soon after he left his Senate seat in 1862.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] When the Southern slave states, including Tennessee, seceded, he remained firmly with the Union.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] He was the only sitting senator from a Confederate state who did not resign his seat upon learning of his state's secession.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In 1862, Lincoln appointed him as military governor of Tennessee after most of it had been retaken.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In 1864, Johnson was a logical choice as running mate for Lincoln, who wished to send a message of national unity in his re-election campaign, especially to ensure the electoral votes of the border states.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Others who were considered for the nomination, at one point or another, were former Senator Daniel Dickinson, Major General Benjamin Butler, Major General William Rosecrans, Joseph Holt, and former Treasury Secretary and Senator John Dix.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic Party was bitterly split between War Democrats and Peace Democrats, a group further divided among competing factions.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Moderate Peace Democrats who supported the war against the Confederacy, such as Horatio Seymour, were preaching the wisdom of a negotiated peace.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] After the Union victory at the Battle of Gettysburg in 1863, moderate Peace Democrats proposed a negotiated peace that would secure Union victory.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] They believed this was the best course of action, because an armistice could finish the war without devastating the South.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Radical Peace Democrats known as Copperheads, such as Thomas H.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Seymour, declared the war to be a failure and favored an immediate end to hostilities without securing Union victory.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan vied for the presidential nomination.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Additionally, friends of Horatio Seymour insisted on placing his name before the convention, which was held in Chicago, Illinois, on August 29–31, 1864.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] But on the day before the organization of that body, Horatio Seymour announced positively that he would not be a candidate.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Since the Democrats were divided by issues of war and peace, they sought a strong candidate who could unify the party.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The compromise was to nominate pro-war General George B.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan for president and anti-war Representative George H.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan, a War Democrat, was nominated for president over the Copperhead Thomas H.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Pendleton, a close associate of the Copperhead Clement Vallandigham, balanced the ticket, since he was known for having strongly opposed the Union war effort.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The convention adopted a peace platform – a platform McClellan personally rejected.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan supported the continuation of the war and restoration of the Union, but the party platform, written by Vallandigham, opposed this position.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The Radical Democratic Convention assembled in Ohio with delegates arriving on May 29, 1864.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] *The New York Times* reported that the hall which the convention organizers had planned to use had been double-booked by an opera troupe.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Almost all delegates were instructed to support Frémont, with a major exception being the New York delegation, which was composed of War Democrats who supported Ulysses S.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Various estimates of the number of delegates were reported in the press; *The New York Times* reported 156 delegates, but the number generally reported elsewhere was 350 delegates.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates came from 15 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] They adopted the name Radical Democratic Party.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] A supporter of Grant was appointed chairman.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The platform was passed with little discussion, and a series of resolutions that bogged down the convention proceedings were voted down decisively.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The convention nominated Frémont for president, and he accepted the nomination on June 4, 1864.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In his letter, he stated that he would step aside if the National Union Convention would nominate someone other than Lincoln for president.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] John Cochrane was nominated for vice president.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 election was the first time since 1812 that a presidential election took place during a war.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] For much of 1864, Lincoln himself believed he had little chance of being re-elected.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Confederate forces had triumphed at the Battle of Mansfield, the Battle of Cold Harbor, the Battle of Brices Cross Roads, the Battle of Kennesaw Mountain and the Battle of the Crater.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In addition, the war was continuing to take a very high toll in terms of casualties with campaigns such as Grant's Overland Campaign and the perceived lack of progress.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The prospect of a long and bloody war started to make the idea of "peace at all cost" offered by the Ultra Peace Democrats look more desirable.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] However, several political and military events eventually made Lincoln's re-election inevitable.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In the first place, the Democrats had to confront the severe internal strains within their party at the Democratic National Convention.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The political compromises made at the Democratic National Convention were contradictory and made McClellan's efforts to campaign seem inconsistent.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Secondly, the Democratic National Convention influenced Frémont's campaign.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont was appalled at the Democratic platform, which he described as "union with slavery".
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] After three weeks of discussions with Cochrane and his supporters, Frémont withdrew from the race in September 1864.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In his statement, Frémont declared that winning the Civil War was too important to divide the Republican vote.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Although he still felt that Lincoln was not going far enough, the defeat of McClellan was of the greatest necessity.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] General Cochrane, who was a War Democrat, agreed and withdrew with Frémont.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] On September 23, 1864, Frémont also brokered a political deal in which Lincoln removed U.S.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Postmaster General Montgomery Blair from office, and on September 24 Abraham Lincoln relieved Blair of his duty as Postmaster General.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan's chances of victory faded after Frémont withdrew from the presidential race.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lastly, with the fall of Atlanta on September 2, there was no longer any question that a Union military victory was inevitable and close at hand.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In the end, the Union Party mobilized the full strength of both the Republicans and the War Democrats under the slogan "Don't change horses in the middle of a stream".
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] It was energized as Lincoln made emancipation the central issue, and state Republican parties stressed the perfidy of the Copperheads.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] 24.4% of the voting age population and 76.3% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The American Civil War was in progress and unfinished during this election.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Because eleven Southern states plus two claimed additional Southern states had declared secession from the Union and formed the Confederate States of America, only twenty-five states participated in the election.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Louisiana and Tennessee had recently been re-captured.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] They chose presidential electors, but their votes were rejected by Congress due to having recently seceded from the Union.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Both states had voted for Lincoln, so it would not have changed the result in any case.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Three new states participated for the first time: Kansas, West Virginia, and Nevada.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan won just three states: Kentucky, Delaware, and his home state of New Jersey.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln won in every state he carried in 1860 except New Jersey, and also carried a state won four years earlier by Stephen Douglas (Missouri), one carried by John C.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Breckinridge (Maryland) and all three newly admitted states (Kansas, Nevada and West Virginia).
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Altogether, 212 electoral votes were counted in Congress for Lincoln – more than enough to win the presidency even if all of the states in rebellion had participated and voted against him.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] This would be the last election in which a party nominee won completely different states than the previous nominee, with McClellan flipping Kentucky and New Jersey, while having lost Missouri.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln was highly popular with soldiers and they in turn recommended him to their families back home.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The following states allowed soldiers to cast ballots: California, Kansas, Kentucky, Maine, Michigan, Rhode Island, and Wisconsin.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Only soldiers from Kentucky gave McClellan a majority of their votes, and he carried the army vote in the state by a vote of 2,823 (70.3%) to 1,194 (29.7%).
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 1,129 counties making returns, Lincoln won in 728 (64.5%), while McClellan carried 400 (35.4%).
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] One county (0.1%) in Iowa split evenly between Lincoln and McClellan.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election the Republicans won in Maryland until 1896.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] (a) *The states in rebellion did not participate in the election of 1864.* (b) *The 17 electoral votes from Tennessee and Louisiana were rejected.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1864-united-states-presidential-election] States in red were won by Republican Abraham Lincoln; states in blue were won by Democrat George B.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1865-state-of-the-union-address] The **1865 State of the Union Address** was written by historian George Bancroft and read to the Congress by Robert Johnson, the son and personal secretary of the 17th president of the United States, Andrew Johnson.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1865-state-of-the-union-address] According to one historian, "Johnson had sent Bancroft only two suggestions: passages from Thomas Jefferson's inaugural and from a speech by Charles James Fox." The result was generally high-toned and well received.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1865-state-of-the-union-address] It was presented to the United States Congress on Monday, December 4, 1865.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1865-state-of-the-union-address] The text stated, "Our thoughts next revert to the death of the late President by an act of parricidal treason.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] The **National Union Convention** (also known as the **Arm-In-Arm Convention**) was held on August 14–16, 1866, in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] The convention was called in Philadelphia before the midterm elections of 1866, in an attempt to encourage political support for US President Andrew Johnson, who was under attack by both moderate and Radical Republicans.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] Johnson's friends tried to rally support for his lenient pro-South Reconstruction policies.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] Some hoped to create a new political party, but that goal was not realized.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] For their part, Republican-aligned newspapers called it the *Rebel–Johnson convention*, insinuating Johnson's true loyalty was to the Confederacy.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] Delegates gathered at a hastily built temporary structure that was designed to accommodate the several thousand people expected to attend.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] Formally called "the Wigwam," the immense edifice was on Girard Avenue, between 19th and 20th Streets, across from Philadelphia's Girard College.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] About 7000 prominent politicians and activists attended the convention.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] At its opening, representatives from Massachusetts (General Darius Nash Couch) and South Carolina (Governor James Lawrence Orr) paraded arm-in-arm to symbolize national reconciliation and social equity.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] The convention was called to order by US Postmaster General Alexander Randall.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] General (and former New York Governor and Senator) John Adams Dix served as the temporary chairman and Wisconsin Senator James R.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] Doolittle served as permanent convention president.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] In the end, the convention was not successful in unifying the country behind Johnson.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] He launched a speaking tour (known as the "Swing Around the Circle") hoping to regain public and political support.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] On the speaking tour, Johnson at times attacked his Republican opponents with crude and abusive language and on several occasions appeared to have had too much to drink.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] Ultimately, the tour was a disaster for Johnson and emboldened Congress to override him and to impeach him in 1868.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] In an effort to counter the National Union Convention's support for Johnson, a group of Southern Radical Republicans who opposed Johnson's Reconstruction policy organized the Southern Loyalists' Convention, which was held on September 3, 1866 in Philadelphia's Independence Hall.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] The September convention voted on a resolution supporting black suffrage.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] Boreman argued against it as "we did not come here to commit suicide" and that passing the resolution would have them "damned to all eternity".
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] Frederick Douglass, attending the convention despite pleas from Oliver P.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] Morton, was one of two black delegates to the convention and argued for passing the resolution.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] On September 7, delegates to the Southern Loyalists' Convention voted to pass a resolution endorsing universal male suffrage.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-national-union-convention] Clement Vallandigham, a copperhead from Ohio, was elected to the convention but withdrew to avoid disturbing the harmony of the convention.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-state-of-the-union-address] The **1866 State of the Union Address** was given by Andrew Johnson, the 17th president of the United States, on Monday, December 3, 1866.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-state-of-the-union-address] This State of the Union was not a spoken address, but a written one.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-state-of-the-union-address] The Reconstruction Era had begun, and Johnson wanted a policy that pardoned the leaders of the Confederate States of America.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/1866-state-of-the-union-address] On additional domestic affairs the President mentioned the rapid construction of the transcontinental railroad, with full completion on track and completion of various treaties with Native Americans tribes that were in rebellion at the beginning of the Civil War.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] The **Andrew Johnson National Cemetery** is a United States National Cemetery on the grounds of the Andrew Johnson National Historic Site in Greeneville, Tennessee.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] Established in 1906, the cemetery was built around the resting place of Andrew Johnson, the 17th President of the United States, and holds more than 2,000 graves.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] Andrew Johnson acquired twenty-three acres outside Greeneville on "Signal Hill" in 1852.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] Winston's *Plebeian and Patriot* (1928), "Though little given to sentiment, he pointed out this spot to a friend, saying that there he wished to rest and to take his final sleep.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] It became known as Signal Hill due to being an excellent place for soldiers to signal to friendly forces.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] When Johnson died, he was buried on the property on August 3, 1875.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] The funeral was performed by Freemasons.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] On June 5, 1878, a 28-foot (8.5 m) tall marble statue was placed by Johnson's grave.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] The monument was considered so dominant that the place came to be known as *Monument Hill*.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] Andrew Johnson's daughter Martha Johnson Patterson willed on September 2, 1898, that the land become a park.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] She further pushed in 1900 to make the site a national cemetery, so that instead of the Johnson family maintaining it, the federal government would.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] The United States Congress chose to make the site a National Cemetery in 1906, and by 1908 the United States War Department took control of it.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] By 1939 there were 100 total graves in the cemetery.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] On May 23, 1942, control of the cemetery went to the National Park Service.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] When the National Park Service was given jurisdiction of the cemetery in 1942, they ruled to allow no more interments, in order to preserve the historic nature of the cemeteries.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] It stopped accepting new burials in 2019, leaving Andersonville National Cemetery as the only National Cemetery under the United States Department of the Interior to accept new burials.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] When the area was made into a cemetery following the death of Andrew Johnson, two of Andrew Johnson's sons were reinterred: Charles Johnson, who had originally been buried in Nashville, Tennessee, and Robert Johnson, originally buried elsewhere in Greeneville.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] Several other members of the Johnson family, including grandchildren, would later be buried in the cemetery.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] Amongst these are his daughter Martha and her husband, former Tennessee United States Senator David T.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] The 26 ft (7.9 m)-tall monument was made in Philadelphia and was paid for by the three surviving Johnson children, Martha, Mary, and Frank.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] The marble monument depicts the United States Constitution, an eagle, and the Bible.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] The cost was said to be US$10,000 (equivalent to $333,621 in 2025) with the carving of the eagle costing US$500 (equivalent to $16,681 in 2025) on its own.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] The base, granite "with a plinth die," is 9 ft 6 in (2.90 m) square.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] Planned speakers for the dedication ceremony were former United States and Confederate States congressman George W.
[src:andrew-johnson-national-cemetery/andrew-johnson-national-cemetery] Jones and biographer of First Ladies Laura C.
